            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Rohan Abramov is a product of a uniquely Bay Area fusion. Born in the early 80s, his mother was a food anthropologist from Mumbai who came to UC Berkeley for her doctorate, while his father was a brilliant, quiet programmer, a Russian Jewish immigrant who had found his calling in the nascent Silicon Valley. Rohan\u2019s childhood in the Inner Richmond was a sensory collage: the scent of his mother\u2019s cardamom and cumin mingling with the logical precision of his father\u2019s code-filled notebooks. This duality\u2014art and science, tradition and innovation\u2014would define his entire life.\n\nInitially, Rohan followed his father\u2019s path, earning a computer science degree and landing a lucrative job during the dot-com boom. But the work felt hollow, a series of abstract problems disconnected from the tangible world. The bubble\u2019s burst in 2001 was his liberation. Laid off and adrift, he rediscovered his passion in the kitchen, not as an artist, but as a scientist. He enrolled in a Master of Science in Food Science and Management program, determined to understand food as a system. This unique qualification made him a perfect fit for the corporate world, not as a line cook, but as a strategic culinary leader.\n\nToday, Rohan is the Corporate Executive Chef for a major arts and entertainment conglomerate headquartered in SoMa. He doesn\u2019t run a single kitchen; he orchestrates the entire culinary experience across a dozen venues, from museum cafes to concert hall bistros. His 5.1-mile commute on the company shuttle provides a quiet window to plan menus that are both sustainable and cutting-edge.\n\nHe lives in Cole Valley with his long-term partner, a landscape architect, in a meticulously restored Victorian. Their life is a quiet rhythm of demanding workweeks followed by weekends spent hiking Mount Sutro or meticulously sourcing ingredients from the Ferry Building Farmers Market. Rohan's ambition isn't to earn a Michelin star, but to pioneer a new model for large-scale sustainable food systems. He dreams of writing a book on the science of nostalgic flavors, finally uniting his mother's warmth with his father's logic on the page."
