            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe\u2019s eight, sitting at the thick oak table in their Inner Richmond flat. To his left, his mother\u2019s brass *masala dabba* releases the scent of toasted cumin. To his right, his father\u2019s pen scratches across graph paper, filling it with clean, logical code. Rohan feels no conflict, only a quiet harmony in the air, a perfect balance he wouldn\u2019t understand for decades. It was the moment he unconsciously learned that logic and warmth could share the same space, a foundational blueprint for his entire life. (Late 1980s)\n\n2.\nThe weight of his keycard was gone. Walking out of the Potrero Hill office for the last time, the dot-com dream collapsing behind him, he expected panic. Instead, as the damp fog rolled in, carrying the scent of eucalyptus, he felt a profound lightness. He wasn't losing a job; he was losing a cage. That sudden, cool breath of real air was the first step on a path back to something tangible, something he could taste and touch. It was the moment of his liberation. (2001)\n\n3.\nIn the sterile light of the university food lab, he stared at the gas chromatograph data for a heirloom tomato. It wasn't just flavor; it was a map of volatile compounds, a precise architecture of nostalgia. In that instant, his father\u2019s meticulous logic and his mother\u2019s sensory kitchen collided with astonishing clarity. He saw food not just as culture, but as a system. This was it\u2014the synthesis he\u2019d been searching for. The moment his career path clicked into place with absolute certainty. (Mid-2000s)\n\n4.\nOn a rare sunny afternoon, hiking the misty trails of Mount Sutro, his partner paused to explain the careful balance of the restored native habitat. He spoke of drainage, sunlight, and how each plant supported the others. Rohan listened, looking from the man he loved to the sprawling city below, and felt a profound sense of peace. He saw the same elegant, systemic thinking he applied to his menus reflected in the landscape. It was a quiet affirmation that they were both building something beautiful and sustainable together. (Late 2010s)\n\n5.\nHe was at the Ferry Building market, squeezing a Sungold tomato, when its uniquely sweet, grassy scent hit him. The sensory rush was pure childhood, a ghost of his mother\u2019s cooking. But it was immediately followed by a clinical thought: *furaneol, hexanal, cis-3-Hexenal*. In that split second, the idea for his book was truly born. Not just a collection of recipes, but a deconstruction of nostalgia itself. The moment he finally knew how to put his father's logic and his mother's heart onto the same page. (Last year)"
